        <svcproc svcproctype="replace" graphiccount="3">
            <title>SERVICE PROCEDURE</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Turn off the engine, remove old belt.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove automatic belt tensioner (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9612091">Figure 1</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Do not remove back side idler pulley. Back side idler pulley must depress belt 1 inch (
                            <hotlnk xrefid="f9612092">Figure 2</hotlnk>).
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="f9612092" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9612092.webp" type="webp" resolution="150"/>
                    <caption>Figure 2.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Mount the manual tensioner assembly to the engine in the location where the automatic
                    tensioner was removed from with an M10 x30 mm hex head bolt (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9612092">Figure 2</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install new belt. Refer to the parts list on page one for the correct
                    <emph type="bold">premium belt</emph>
                    for the model vehicle being serviced.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With the tensioner assembly at the top of its mounting bolt slot (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9612092">Figure 2</hotlnk>), rotate entire tensioner assembly into position (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9612093">Figure 3</hotlnk>). Tighten the M10 hex head bolt to 30 ft-lbs. (40.6 Nm).
                </para>
                <figure id="f9612093" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9612093.webp" type="webp" resolution="150"/>
                    <caption>Figure 3.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With the flange nut loose on the tensioner pulley (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9612093">Figure 3</hotlnk>), turn the adjusting bolt until the belt reaches the
                    correct tension (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9612094">Figure 4</hotlnk>). Tighten the belt to 25 to 30 lbs. tension for each rib
                    on the belt, 150 to 180 lbs. total tension.
                </para>
                <figure id="f9612094" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9612094.webp" type="webp" resolution="150"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tighten the flange nut on the tensioner pulley to 50 to 75 ft-lbs. (67 to 101 Nm) to
                    hold belt tension (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9612094">Figure 4</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Run the engine to check belt operation. Check belt tension. After a 10 minute run-in,
                    the belt tension should be 120 to 150 lbs.
                </para>
            </step1>
